      <li><strong>Best under $100: De'Longhi Stilosa</strong> — strongest beginner-friendly shot quality and upgrade path at entry pricing.</li>
      <li><strong>Best $100-$149: CASABREWS 3700GENSE</strong> — best milk-drink value with faster heat-up and usable steam power.</li>
      <li><strong>Best $150-$200: Mr. Coffee Café Barista</strong> — easiest latte/cappuccino workflow for users prioritizing convenience over manual control.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>1) De'Longhi Stilosa — Best Overall Espresso Machine Under $200</h3>
    <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Best for most first-time buyers who want real pump espresso without paying for unnecessary extras.</p>
    <p><strong>Buy this if...</strong> you want a reliable starter machine with enough control to improve your shots over time.</p>
    <p><strong>Skip this if...</strong> you want one-button milk drinks with minimal manual input.</p>
    <ProsCons
      pros={["Consistent shots for the price when paired with fresh grounds.", "Simple layout makes learning less intimidating.", "Common replacement parts are easy to find."]}
      cons={["Steam wand performance is workable, not café-tier.", "Small drip tray needs frequent emptying."]}
    />
    <p><strong>Key specs:</strong> Semi-auto · 15-bar pump claim · pressurized basket · manual steam wand · 33.8 oz tank · Espresso-capable: Yes.</p>
    <p><strong>Retention/static note:</strong> No built-in grinder; shot consistency depends heavily on your external grinder dose retention and static control.</p>
    <p><strong>Why it wins this slot:</strong> It delivers the best all-round blend of entry price, controllable shots, and long-term learning headroom.</p>

    <h3>2) Mr. Coffee Café Barista — Best Beginner Milk Workflow</h3>
    <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Best for latte-heavy households that want easier milk drinks and less manual steaming practice.</p>
